\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Linearizing deformations of the harmonic source-filter model with the spiral
 scattering transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Vincent Lostanlen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A classical model for voised speech production consists in the convolution
 of a harmonic glottal source 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)$
\end_inset

 with a vocal tract filter 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Introducing indepedent deformations to both components brings realistic
 variability to pitch and spectral envelope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(t)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{+\infty}\delta(t-2\pi n)
\]

\end_inset

be a Dirac pulse train of period 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 The Poisson summation formula
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
see Wavelet Tour, Theorem 2.4.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 states that the Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)$
\end_inset

 is a harmonic comb of fundamental frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{e}(\omega)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{+\infty}\exp(-\mathrm{i}k\omega).
\]

\end_inset

The equality holds in a distributional sense 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
see Wavelet Tour, Section A.1.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{\theta}(t)=\left(e\circ\theta\right)(t)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{+\infty}\delta(\theta(t)-2\pi n).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=[e_{\theta}\ast h_{\nu}](t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
